    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna and it mentioned the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed and why it's so important?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube works by measuring the difference between the static pressure of the surrounding air and the high dynamic pressure of air moving directly into the tube at the plane's nose. This pressure difference is converted into an airspeed reading that allows pilots to know exactly how fast they are flying relative to the air mass. This measurement is critical because it enables proper flying by preventing stalls, managing takeoff and landing speeds, and avoiding dangerous options like flying without wind resistance.",
      "source": "target",
